{"cursor":"28211","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Tidal acceleration' is an effect of the tidal forces between an orbiting\nnatural satellite (e.g. the Moon), and the primary planet that it orbits (e.g.\nthe Earth). The acceleration is usually negative, as it causes a gradual slowing\nand recession of a satellite in a prograde orbit away from the primary, and a\ncorresponding slowdown of the primary's rotation. The process eventually leads\nto tidal locking of first the smaller, and later the larger body. The EarthâMoon\nsystem is the best studied case.\n\nThe similar process of 'tidal deceleration' occurs for satellites that have an\norbital period that is shorter than the primary's rotational period, or that\norbit in a retrograde direction.\n","linknr":324,"url":"Tidal_acceleration","recorded":1362268732,"links":33,"instances":["moon","moon","moon","moon","moon","moon","moon","1952_standard","moon","moon","moon","moon","moon","moon","moon","moon","moon","moon","moon","moon","moon","moon","moon","astronomy"],"pdf":["http://rstl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/19/215-235/160.full.pdf","http://rstl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/46/491-496/162.full.pdf","http://www.academie-sciences.fr/membres/in_memoriam/Lalande/Lalande_pdf/Mem1786_p390.pdf","http://archive.numdam.org/article/ASENS_1879_2_8__361_0.pdf","http://rstl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/143/397.full.pdf","http://rstl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/143/397.full.pdf","http://www.leapsecond.com/history/1968-Metrologia-v4-n4-Essen.pdf","http://naif.jpl.nasa.gov/pub/naif/generic_kernels/spk/planets/de421_lunar_ephemeris_and_orientation.pdf","http://rsta.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/351/1695/165.full.pdf","http://www.physics.ucsd.edu/~tmurphy/apollo/doc/Dickey.pdf","http://www.physics.ucsd.edu/~tmurphy/apollo/doc/Dickey.pdf"],"categories":["Tides","Geodesy","Orbits","Orbit of the Moon"],"headings":["Earth–Moon system","Other cases of tidal acceleration","Tidal deceler